courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand the fundamental physics of solar collector, thermal energy storage, and photovoltaic cells and systems and to investigate the solar cell efficiency;
(2) use wind speed data to evaluate wind energy, design and select wind turbines;
(3) investigate the hydraulic energy and design and select water turbines, and the associated environmental risk and impact;
(4) know fundamental chemistry of biomass energy systems, conversion technologies for gasification and liquefaction of biomass feedstocks, and ecological aspects of biomass energy systems;
(5) understand the principle of thermoelectric effect, thermoelectric generator, and its design and application;
(6) understand the general principles of fuel cells and batteries, hydrogen production and storage, and application in transportation;
(7) conduct assigned lab experiments to get familiar with several different renewable energy systems.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to apply mathematical and economic techniques in supply and demand of energy, energy markets, and carbon auditing;
(2) be able to assess the impact of government policies and regulations;
(3) acquire basic knowledge of the history of energy use and understanding of the current challenges facing the energy system;
(4) evaluate and compare the outcomes of different energy and environmental projects.

This course contributes to the following EEEN Programme Learning Outcomes:
(1) E1: Acquired basic knowledge related to energy and environmental engineering, including physics, mathematics, thermodynamics, energy technologies, power systems, environmental economics, building control and assessment, air pollution, etc. (K,S);
(2) E6: Acquired the understanding of professional and ethical responsibilities in the field of energy and environmental engineering (V);
(3) E7: Developed proficiency in technical communication (both oral and written) (S);
(4) E8: Acquired a broad understanding of the importance of economic, environmental, political, social and other global implications of energy and environment-related issues (V);
(5) E9: Acquired knowledge in historical and contemporary issues (S,V);
(6) E13: Established a good understanding and vision of the energy and environmental industries in terms of technologies, tradeoffs and impacts (K).

K = Knowledge outcomes; S = Skills outcomes; V = Values and attitude outcomes.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand the fundamentals of psychrometrics, air-handling process;
(2) understand the working principles of the single-zone systems, CAV and VAV systems;
(3) understand the working principles of the hydronic system and central plant;
(4) understand the fundamentals of thermal comfort, ventilation and indoor air quality.

